Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @chilli{1}(halved lengthways, deseeded and finely chopped) lengthways, deseed and finely chop.

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and chopped widthways into small pieces).

Place a #pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the @turkey mince{250%g} until cooked through, ~{6-8%mins}. Break it up with a #spoon{} as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the turkey is cooked, add the onion, garlic, scallion and chilli.

> Use less chilli if you don't like spice.

Cook until the veg is softened, ~{2-3%mins}.

Add the pak choi to the pan.

Stir-fry until just softened, ~{3-4%mins}.

Stir in the @ketjap manis{2%sachets} and @soy sauce{1%sachet} and allow to warm through.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(chopped, stalks and all).

> TIP: Add a splash of @?water{to taste} if the sauce becomes too thick.

Carefully separate the @udon noodles{300%g}.

Add to the pan and gently toss to coat in the sauce and warm through, ~{1-2%mins}.

Share the tangy turkey noodles between #bowls{}.

Garnish with the chopped coriander.